The first virtual operator will arrive in the Czech Republic this year.
Probably
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite developed and our operators offer practically all services as their Western European partners.
However, here we still lack something - the virtual operator, which would force those to be cheaper.
It will probably not take long to arrive.
That the Czech operators are part of the most expensive in Europe, we have already written it on mobil.cz.
The rest was also confirmed by the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTÚ), which warned that the price of SMS messages in our country is of the most expensive in the entire Union.
After the European Commission’s latest steps in the field of roaming rates regulation it is likely to come to a paradox situation – for some customers of Czech mobile operators the SMS they send from abroad will be cheaper than if they send them from home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of competition that really wants to fight.
Probably this seems paradoxical to us, because we have three mobile networks and their high coverage is more than 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to regret that in the Czech market there is an extreme competition.
From this also the chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTÚ), Pavel Dvořák, has already expressed that there is no more place in the Czech Republic for any other operator.
It is true that for a classic operator with its own network it no longer has too many possibilities (for the rest, it would be very difficult to find some frequency).
However, there is still one possibility - the virtual operator.
Precisely the entrance of the virtual operator to the mobile phone market brought a remarkable price decline before which the classic operators had to react.
At the same time, even before the entry of shark like Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile to the UK market, similar voices were heard both there and here.
It has been shown that there is a place for this type of operators and that they can succeed.
There is no need to look for examples too far.
In February of this year we inform you about the launch of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
Just after half a year, this operator managed to get more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest operator in the neighboring country.
On the other hand, behind Mobilking is the group Penta which, in addition, in the Czech Republic is the owner of U:fon.
The advantage of virtual operators is in the possibility of focusing on many more specific target groups.
In addition, so that they can work effectively, it is enough for them to have many less customers than a classic operator.
They do not carry relatively large expenses on the construction, operation and maintenance of the network.
In the world, this type of virtual operators normally profile with low expenses - they offer cheap calls and SMS messages that, however, are often contrary to the offer of more tailored services.
Thus, for example, Mobile Tesco in Britain offers SMS at least half the cheap with respect to the competition.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows can be a good blow also the bet for a nothing trivial target group.
This operator is specifically directed to the man.
"The right man chooses Mobilking - it's the operator you like and who you can trust," says David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, who works this virtual operator.
It’s hard to say if a similar concept like that of Poland could engage in our country.
Vodafone spokesman Miroslav Čepický said: “The Czech market is relatively small to access by segments on which the majority of virtual operators are based.
In addition, from the point of view of the offer of services is relatively saturated.”
In the Czech Republic there are no possibilities, mobile operators say
However, it seems almost certain that if in the Czech Republic there will be some virtual operator that will not be Mobilking.
“We’re talking about the expansion of this successful project, however, in the Czech Republic it doesn’t seem too hopeful.
It’s rather the launch of Mobilking in other countries in our region,” said Jana Studničková, a spokesman for the Penta financial group, in a telephone conversation to mobil.cz.
He indirectly assured that the current mobile telephone operators in the Czech Republic definitely do not tend to this idea.
Instead, they try to do everything they can so that there is no potential competition.
Interest about the launch of a virtual mobile operator already shows it the GTS Novera group that would like to take a step further to become a real competition of Telefónica O2 in the field of business customers.
“We have a great interest in this, to be able to offer our customers not only fixed telephony services but also mobile telephony.
And the earlier, the better.
With this possibility we have met repeatedly with all the Czech mobile phone operators.
With some of them we have managed to advance in the meetings,” said group spokesman Pavel Kaidl.
And then, they may have better times.
It seems that, by non-official information, the first official operator would have to arrive possibly already at the end of the year.
But for now its appearance is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
“At this point we believe that the situation is suitable for the appearance of a virtual operator in the Czech market.
The Czech market compared to others is a very specific market.
Until now no one has addressed us with some complex and serious project on this ground,” said Vlastimil Sršeň, spokesman for Telefónica O2.
The specificity of the Czech market refers to other operators.
T-mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrová, in exceptional compliance with O2’s opinion, adds: “From today we have not recorded any viable commercial project that, bilaterally profitable, may continue to develop.”
“In T-Mobile’s network it will be difficult to find some virtual operator until the end of the year.
At this moment we should already have on the table some concrete contract that would be possible to study in such a short horizon.”
Vodafone focuses on compliance with the requirements of a 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický adds: “We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and this in terms of expenditure and infrastructure allocation.
We consider it the greatest contribution from the point of view of our customers.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this field lies in the partner with whom to establish a shared network for a fast internet on the mobile.”
Responsible offices - with nuts and meat operators
The progress of mobile operators can be easily understood, but the entry of another operator would mean increasing competition which would lead to a price decline and thus a profit decline.
So why make it easier to enter the competition?
When the operators want to get something, they are able to throw from the same corner, proof of this is the grip when U:fon emerged.
Per the greatest pressure to the ČTÚ was at the time of the U:fon entrance by the company T-Mobile.
This is confirmed by the public information accessible on the website of the ČTÚ.
But just now U:fon serves as an argument of why not accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová adds to this: “In addition, not long ago the competitive environment in the mobile phone market was open to a fourth operator.
With regard to the character of the mobile phone market in the Czech Republic it is natural that the entry of another player into the market would imply great demands for him and, above all, for his services.”
That’s why this access to mobile operators is tremendously disanimating due to the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulatory body.
It is not just the position of the ČTU, which unfortunately has no competition to intervene in commercial tender, unlike Britain and other developed countries.
This belongs purely to the Office for the Protection of Commercial Offers (UOHS).
However, it expressed its typical attitude to this problem.
“The entrance of a virtual operator to the mobile phone market would be possible after a contract on the rental of the necessary infrastructure between a mobile operator and a virtual operator was concluded.
Until today no agreement has been closed since the offer of the potential stakeholders was not interesting enough for classical operators,” added Kristián Chalupa, from the UOHS Department of Foreign Relations.
These statements do not surprise the representatives of the operators.
For the offices that must represent the interests of consumers it is something more than a consideration, besides that they must observe that no one takes advantage of their position on the market.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: "In the abroad where virtual operators work normally we can observe that their entry into the market contributed to the price decrease of mobile phone services"
Evidently, the pressure on the proper functioning of the market media and the price decline do not enter the interests of the UOHS.
Really the dramatically shocking thing in all this case lies in the dissonant reactions resulting from the three mobile operators.
The question of whether it really is a coincidence, is offered by itself.
It’s the same as with the price of the gasoline in the gasoline since it’s clear that it’s work of coincidence and a hard struggle for competition.
“The Office in this sense has not found signs of unfair competition and therefore has no reason to somehow intervene.
None of the operators have a dominant position therefore do not have a corresponding rise of responsibility in their performance on the market.
The tools needed to open the mobile phone market to virtual operators, rather, lack, as well as telecommunications regulators,” Chalupa added.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of the many conflict points.
Evidently there is an analysis of relevant markets developed by the CTU according to which telecommunications are from the point of view of commercial tendering a single market.
In this type of market naturally none of the Czech operators have a dominant position.
However, some of the legal experts offer another vision - for a virtual operator to arise it is always necessary the agreement with the network administrator.
And the mobile phone operator - with all its logic - has the monopoly of its network.
Therefore, in a particular segment it must necessarily be dominant.
And if this argument was not accepted, at least for UOHS it should represent a warning the fact that three mobile operators rise strikingly similarly.
The current complaints of the interested parties (including the aforementioned company GTS Novera) show that in all negotiations with the operators clash with many similar obstacles.
Carrying responsibility in the ČTÚ is a fairly common trick in the field of telecommunications of which the UOHS laves the hands in all this matter.
We have met him in some similar cases.
Unfortunately recently a new amendment to the telecommunications law was submitted to the expansion of the competition of the ČTÚ in the field of commercial tenderings that was not taken into effect, even when a series of specialists promised that the situation would improve.
This should be perfectly known by UOHS representatives, but it is obvious that their interests are elsewhere.
Everything goes well when no one looks.
At the same time, unnoticably continues to work something like a pseudovirtual operator that in the Czech mobile telephone networks already exists a few.
They are companies that put their own prices on mobile phone services that, however, only one part are public.
These are usually companies that are dedicated to multi-level marketing.
Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile phone services.
Usually, only a few selected people get the price list of these companies.
The magic is that the company, with respect to the operator, acts as a classic business client of the same, charging a lot of SIM cards.
As a special customer, you will then receive special prices and other offers.
The problem is that the commercial conditions in all Czech mobile operators prohibit this type of return.
“If such cases were discovered, we could talk about infringement in the contract conditions that could be translated into the end of collaboration with the given society,” said Martina Kemrová.
But it is quite unlikely that an activity of this type carried out by mobile telephone operators will not reach responsible people.
Exactly in the case of the three companies mentioned may come to deal with thousands of customers.
None of the operators are against this procedure.
With the activities of these companies they get some unpredictable profits and, at the same time – unlike authentic virtual operators – in no way threaten their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický warns us of the possible problems: “the law allows a speculation of this kind, however, the services of this company are used only by a disappointing so much percentage of customers.
These, in addition, must accept that the SIM card of your phone is not at your name so they can’t have it absolutely as a normal customer of the operators.”
This is exactly what it should seem to the CTU at least strange.
There is also a new question for the UOHS.
If mobile phone operators turn their eyes into this type of procedure, why do they block the virtual operator’s entry?
It is necessary to add that the UOHS has the sufficient competence to discover this type of activities and if it is that it will not want it should not be satisfied with the explanations of the operators that they have no idea of this story and that their commercial conditions do not allow it.
When will we stop being the most expensive?
As it was already clear in the text, the entrance of the virtual operator to the mobile phone market brought a significant drop in services prices.
At the same time, practically in all countries where the virtual operator emerged, the classic operators tried more or less to protect themselves from this irruption.
The arguments used by these were practically all identical - too small, a market, eventually, too saturated, problems with the quality of the service, etc.
In the most advanced countries, however, at this time the regulatory bodies have intervened and in no case defended the operators but their customers.
With formal measures or informal pressure they succeeded in the first virtual operator to emerge and with it others began to emerge.
Unfortunately, the Czech Regulatory Authority all this case happens as if it were a burning key.
By our experience, we can not cease to be impressed that the confusion of attributions in these cases suits them.
But let’s not desperate.
If this information between backgrounds is correct and the virtual operator really reaches these lands, then the Czech mobile market probably begins to move again.
If any of the operators let any mobile virtual operator enter, it will be difficult for the UOHS to remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of other stakeholders.
And we may stop calling more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
The new Czech hymn has four new versions.
Choose the best
Listen to the four presentations of the new version of the Czech official hymn.
On Sunday, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek on the occasion of the day of the Czech official celebrations presented the new official recording of the hymn Where, my home.
The new hymn was recorded by the National Theatre Orchestra under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
There are four versions available - two versions that are Solos, one with male voice and one with female voice, one with Coro and one with instrumental.
The song is performed by Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka.
The authors of the arrangements of the hymn are Otakar Jeremiáš and Jaroslav Krček.
On the iHNed.cz server you can listen to the four versions.
Bělohlávek considers this Czech national singer as one of the most beautiful hymns.
The Czech Radio has already said before that it intentionally chose for the Solos singers with representatively young voices that are more expressive and popular.
“From the beginning I’ve tried with the two and then, also, with the Corus to fix in the diction so that the text was well understood, so that it had consonance,” he commented.
The Czech official hymn celebrates its 175th anniversary next year.
The song Where, My Home sounded for the first time in the year 1834 on the tables of the Theatre of the States in the original Czech work Fidlovačka by Josef Kajetán Tyl and arranged with the music by František Škroup.
It gained popularity and people made it theirs.
The first strike of the song after the emergence of Czechoslovakia in the year 1918 became, naturally, a part of the official hymn.
One of the seven official symbols remained even after the emergence of the independent Czech Republic.
