Talking asleep
Some children talk at night.
I am not referring to those who wake up very awake telling us something that has passed the day before, but to children who speak while sleeping.
The first time it happens, you probably get a shame, but it really doesn’t matter.
It is a benign alteration of sleep that is called somnilochios.
It is very common, especially in children and adolescents.
More than one has been told that he talked in the evening.
This phenomenon can appear very sporadically (one time in life for example associated with an episode of high fever), or more periodically (every day, once a week, once in months ...), the next day the child doesn’t remember anything.
There is no single cause that determines its appearance.
They are often related to other sleep disorders such as nightmares, night terrors, night enuresis, or sleeping, but there is no reason to be so.
As we have mentioned above, they can also be associated with very high fever images, stress situations or over-excitation.
This is a little studied phenomenon.
The intensity with which it appears is also very variable.
It can be that you speak in a quiet voice tone, loose words, a murm or all the opposite (writing, crying, long speeches...).
In cases where the manifestation is very intense it would be appropriate to observe the child and consult with a specialist, to check if there is any question that is generating a lot of anxiety and gives him out of this way.
We have said that it is a beneficial alteration, therefore it has no treatment, unless it is associated with another sleep alteration that can be treated (for example, if it is associated with sleep apnea or a stress picture).
What can be done is to take into account a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child much before going to sleep.
Therefore, look for quiet games and avoid TV shows or series that are fearful or a bit violent.
With very nervous children and they hard to relax, relaxation techniques can be used to help them acquire some internal calm.
This will help the child to have a quiet sleep.
Once the sleeps appear, try to keep the calm.
Remember that they are harmless for the child and that the next day he will not remember anything of what has happened.
useful advice
Do not wake him up.
It is useless, because he is not conscious, and you will break his dream.
Although he is talking, he is sleeping and therefore is resting.
Remember that if it is very angry during several episodes it would be convenient to consult or find out what is what generates so much anxiety in the child.
If you understand what you say (which is not the most common), don’t fall into the temptation to make him an interrogation to sound him information.
You won’t get anything, because when you’re asleep, you’re not aware of how to organize your thought.
You will also hear what he says, but you don’t know what he is dreaming about to say that, so very careful in how you interpret the information and with the conclusions you draw.
Never tell the child that you can ask him at night to know his secrets.
Not even a joke.
This generates a lot of anxiety.
In short, don’t worry, it’s nothing bad, it’s an episode that lasts just a few minutes.
