Review: Blood Is Back Safe
Héma-Québec celebrated its 10th anniversary yesterday, and its president, Francine Décary, was right to rejoice, because Héma-Québec has again become one of the safest and most effective blood suppliers in the world.
And above all, it regained the public's confidence that had been seriously vacillated by the contaminated blood scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As you know, the national blood reserves administered by the Canadian Red Cross Blood Transfusion Service have been contaminated by the Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) and the Hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
Faced with this drama and public dissatisfaction, the Canadian government made in February 1994 a public survey, headed by judge Horacio Krever, which intended to clarify the circumstances that had led to such a tragedy and to formulate recommendations so that such a disaster should not be reproduced anymore.
While Judge Krever was delayed to present his relationship, certain provinces then created a committee aimed at planning a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau committee fulfilled this mission.
According to Gélineau and Krever reports, two suppliers have been created in Canada: Héma-Québec to supply Quebec and the Canadian Society of Blood to supply all the other provinces and both territories.
“In 1998, when Héma-Québec began its activities, almost 38% of people still trusted the blood system in Quebec,” Decary recalls.
The situation was disanimating.
After doing a lot of effort to improve the safety of blood products and a lot of work over the years that followed, we have recovered the public’s confidence,” he says before proudly affirming that at the beginning of 2008, 94% of the Quebec population had in the successive confidence in Héma-Quebec.
Dr. Decary reminds, however, that “confidence is something extremely fragile.”
Since its establishment, on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec applied the principle of precaution.
At that time, we witnessed in Europe the birth of numerous cases of the human variant of the crazy cow disease, a new variant of the Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease.
And we didn’t know if this disease could be transmitted through the blood.
Then we support one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports, according to which when we don’t know it and when a serious disease can emanate from that, in this case the Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease that is characterized by a degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death, we introduce measures of exclusion.
In April 1999, we denied the blood of people who had stayed in the UK for more than a month since 1980.
But, a few years ago, it has been demonstrated out of doubt that this disease is transmitted through the blood.
This episode showed us so that the principle of precaution that was applied was meaningful.”
In 1999 a much more sensitive HIV detection technique appeared on the market: the nucleic acid tests that allow to detect directly in the blood of donors the presence of the virus and not the antibodies against the virus, in which the tests used so far were founded.
Nucleic acid tests allowed to shorten the period between the time the person has been infected and the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, the specialist explains.
We could reduce this period to less than a week.
We thus substantially decrease the risk that certain donors are infected without knowing it and that we cannot detect them.
These improvements allowed to significantly reduce the risk of getting AIDS through a blood transfusion.
Today, one in every 12 million people is at risk of receiving HIV-infected blood.
“This means that 12 million blood products will have to be distributed before someone is infected with HIV.
So as Héma-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it will take more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmission by a blood product survives.
I think you can today receive or prescribe a blood transfusion to recover health without concerns,” said Héma-Québec head of the headquarters.
“Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
It is never known which pathogen could emerge in the system.
Last year, the Chikungunya virus appeared on the Island of the Meeting, which, for example, the West Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
You have to be constantly vigilant," Dr. Decary pursues before emphasizing that in addition to a secure supply, Héma-Québec should also predict a sufficient supply.
“The needs are increasing because the population is aging.
Since the most aggressive anti-cancer treatments, patients often need an injection of red blood cells or tablets.
The population aging also has consequences on the network of blood donors that regains by average term only 3% of Quebecs admissible to blood donation.
All people with good health, aged 18 and who meet the criteria of admissibility can donate blood every 56 days, i.e. six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who offer their blood are not accepted, because they suffer from AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have travelled to a country where malaria reigns, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
“With this 3% we managed to maintain an inventory that covers the needs of hospitals.
Penurias are very rare.
But members of this network of donors need to be renewed as they age and can no longer donate their blood.
But it’s hard to convince people to donate their blood, but above all to retain them and encourage them to be a regular donor.
Since today’s life is very untouched, we rarely find the time to spend an hour to donate their blood,” Francine Décary afflicts.
With a budget of $297 million annually, Héma-Québec supplies not only blood products, but also human tissues, including bone injections, heart valves, eye balls and skin that is almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analyzed, transformed and frozen before being stored in Hema-Quebec, which also manages the only public blood bank of the umbilical cord in Quebec.
The umbilical cord that was formerly considered biomedical waste is filled with a rich blood of stem cells that can be used for the treatment of serious diseases such as leukemia.
“We’ve celebrated a few weeks ago, the placement in the bank of our millennial blood sample of the umbilical cord and is expected to get out more than a thousand of these per year.
We would have to start proposing it for injections at the beginning of the coming year,” says Doctora Décary who describes this cordon blood take program as very popular.
