Wall Street rescue operation - Democrats and Republicans agree
The Bush administration and Congress leaders, both Republicans and Democrats, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the most important economic rescue plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the $700 billion plan that aims to remove the financial crisis that shocks Wall Street for months has to be still confirmed by both Congress Chambers.
In particular, it provides for: a better control by the elected of its implementation, of new mechanisms aimed at ensuring the refund of the public money invested, of the new provisions to contain the number of houses embarked the lack of payment, as well as a right of supervision on the wages paid to the managers of the rescued companies.
The U.S. Treasury Secretary, Henry Paulson, the President of the House of Representatives, Nancy Pelosi, and the Republican representative at the negotiation table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced the good news a few minutes after midnight, yesterday, at the end of a negotiation marathon that lasted two days.
“We have made great progress with a view to an agreement that will be effective on the markets,” Bush administration representative Henry Paulson said.
“Everything has been done to cover the economy and the ordinary Americans with the current crisis in Wall Street,” the Democrat explained.
“It’s the fundamental point: if we don’t do this, the trauma, chaos and disturbances on the daily life of the Americans will be immense,” said Republican Judd Gregg.
The negotiations had ended very quickly in the last hours because they feared the effect that would cause a new failure in the humour of investors.
The last time that had been fixed was the opening of the markets this morning.
The two candidates in the U.S. presidential elections, who have adhered late to the negotiations, showed themselves rather favorable to the deal, without forgetting yet to express their dissatisfaction of being forced to reach this extremity.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama gave him certain provisions to reach the agreement, the one that would allow owners to preserve their home and the one over the salary of the leaders of the companies surviving by the state.
“When the taxpayers are asked to take extraordinary measures due to the irresponsibility of some, there is no need to congratulate.
But these measures are necessary,” he commented on American television.
His Republican opponent, John McCain, Interrogated in another chain to know if he would vote for the proposed plan, he replied that: "I would like to see the details, but I hope to vote for it."
“The important points I read [most] that it is something that we will have to digest and with which we will be able to advance.
He said that the option of not doing anything is not acceptable.”
The 700 billion plan aims to buy with the money of the taxpayers the doubtful debts, the risky and invendible assets of the U.S. financial institutions.
It comes after 14 months of a crisis caused by the outbreak of a real estate bubble that first led to the sinking of risk mortgage credits before spreading to other more common forms of credit bonds (PCAAs) and provoking a liquidity frozen and a banks and financial institutions dismissal.
It is a group of elected Republicans who had made the first draft agreement change, last week.
We believe that we have gone out of the stagnation since the Democrats accepted that certain “toxic” assets of the difficulties are only insured by the government, rather than purchased.
