Psychology of overwhelming: Why do we spend more money?
Participants in the auction are likely to spend more money and overvaluate the product.
Neurologists and economists at the University of New York discovered the neurological-economic bases of this known and apparently irrational behavior.
According to the study appeared in the journal Science, people don’t want to lose in competitions like eBay auctions, so they prefer to pay even an excessive price.
Scientists tried to establish the neurological scheme of this "game" by means of experimental discounts.
One of the volunteer groups played lottery, the other participated in an auction and while examined through the functional magnetic resonance system (fMRI) the active areas of the brain of the people participating in the experiment.
In both games they could earn money the participants, but during the auctions, where it is the fundamental element to bet more than the other, by losing the game was intensified the operation of the complex called stretch located below the brain cortex.
This area of the brain, in addition to many other functions, plays a role in the "auto-premium" mechanism of the nervous system.
According to scientists, the increase in bets is explained as a prevention to not cause an intense reaction of the stretch.
To fundamentate their theory, the economists of the scientific group also conducted a financial monitoring study.
In this experiment, three groups bet against one person in different circumstances.
The control group was simply communicated the actual value of the product in question, and its members bet.
Another group, in addition to this, was promised that if they win, they would receive $15 more prize.
Instead, the third group received exactly $15 before the auction, but in case of losing the auction the group members lost even that money.
So the only difference between the two groups was that for one the triumph was highlighted and for the other the failure.
However, checking the hypothesis of the neurologists, the members of the group that played "contra failure" were willing to bet even more than the members of the control group and the "winner" group.
"These results cannot be deducted from any previous economic theory.
For those so far explained the phenomena of the auctions only with the joy of winning and with the prevention of risks.
Only visual neurological methods helped solve this contradiction between the two theories, so now we get to a third explanation,” said Andrew Schotter, professor at the Faculty of Economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When should you go to the doctor?
In the world about five hundred million people suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary the chronic liver disease is considered one of the main causes of death.
The number of infected in this country is estimated at a hundred thousand, but only seven thousand are treated because many of the sick do not know they are infected.
The denomination of hepatitis is the common name of different liver diseases caused by viruses.
The symptoms are very similar; the liver infection and icterism are characteristic, but their pathogens and caused diseases are very different.
Hepatitis viruses depending on the pathogen are spread by two main forms: hepatitis A and E by food (for example with water or food contained), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and body humors (sperm, vagina mood, saliva).
It is recommended for travelers to be protected by vaccination against the virus A and B, against the C there are no vaccines.
The symptoms of hepatitis A appear two or three weeks after consuming infected food, manifested by a general bad condition, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After this appear on the skin and on the white of the eyes the icterism, the excrement is made clear, the dark-colored urine and healing can last even two to three weeks.
Every year a million people die in the world from hepatitis B-caused cancer and liver cirrhosis, the most serious forms of this disease.
The main reason for this is that according to the calculations, only one in ten infected people receive pharmacological treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: without treatment it can produce liver cirrhosis and even cancer.
Most infected people don’t know they’re sick because this pathological agent gradually destroys liver cells and often the first symptoms only appear 20-30 years later.
Therefore, premature recognition, systematic medical control is very important.
This disease is much more common in three groups: people who had blood transfusion before 1991, drug consumers and those who carry tattoos.
Today there are about 200 million people worldwide suffering from chronic hepatitis C.
As this disease can be discovered with a routine laboratory control too, it is worth consulting the family doctor when experiencing some unknown symptoms.
The disease has healing if it is discovered in time, it is possible to exterminate the virus from the body, so you can suppress the infection and prevent cancer.
September 30 is the World Hepatitis Day, which was organized for the first time in 2004 by organizations representative of the sick.
Its objective is to draw attention to the causes of chronic liver infections caused by viruses and to the importance of their premature recognition.
Does it hurt anyone who believes in God?
According to the results of a recent investigation, religious faith has a calming effect that also relieved the death of the Catholic martyrs.
Scientists at the University of Oxford conducted an interesting experiment: they analyzed how religious beliefs influence human pain, the British newspaper Telegraph.
In the framework of this singular experiment they applied electric shock to 12 Catholic believers and the same number of atheists, while all were looking at a painting of the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to exclude most of their pain.
Thanks to the human brain scan technique, it was possible to verify that Catholic believers were able to activate that part of their brain that is responsible for the pain regulation.
This experiment is the first of the series of research in which alongside the academics participate also scientists, philosophers and theologists of the different departments of the University.
The analysis took place in the following way; they fixed a scratching instrument on the patient's left hand, which applied the electric shock.
The researchers asked the participants of the experiment to fix their look in two paintings; the 17th century Sassoferrat's Virgin Mary and the 15th century Leonardo da Vinci's Army Lady.
The researchers had the hope that the show of the Virgin Mary would cause a certain religious mood among the faithful, as they chose Leonardo's oil because it wasn't too different from the other, and they thought it had a calming effect.
The patients spent half an hour on a MRI scanner, receiving in that period 20 electrical shocks in four successive parts while observing the painting of religious or the other theme.
The Catholics affirmed that when they looked at the Virgin Mary they felt in “safe” as “protected” people, “they calmed themselves and in their heart reigned peace.”
When they watched the religious theme picture, they felt 12 percent less pain than when they watched Leonardo’s work.
The psychologist Miguel Farias who also participated in the experiment, thinks that with any image so shocking you can get a similar effect with the atheists too, you just have to find the right image.
“We should find the portrait of a person they feel very positively, like a mother or a father,” the psychologist said.
Anglican bishop Tom Wright celebrated the result of the investigation.
“Exercise of faith should and in many cases really changes our personality,” Wright added.
After these formidable results there is only one question: what effect would it have for pain regulation if the faithful were shown the Madonna of Leonardo or of another painter of its size?
Would the vision of a high-quality Virgin Mary bring even better results?
