At the question what’s going to happen in five years Schmidt answered as follows: I would like Google to be able to answer questions like “What to do tomorrow?” or “What would be the job that best suits me?” – however, the software will not be able to answer apparently so simple questions as long as there is not enough information from users.
Not all internet users are aware that during their network browsing, the searched keywords, IP addresses and the pages they passed through are accurately stored.
Thanks for example to Personalized Search that debuted two years ago, users can store their own browsing history, can again consult what they searched before, what they opened and thanks to this history will generate much more personalized searches – on this same logic will be based on the Recommendations, in which the system will offer us products and services based on the previously defined and stored preferences.
What will happen if they take advantage of my data against me, if they collect information about my activities? - ask those users who are concerned with seeing Google's informative monopoly.
In most cases rather the potential represented by the company is what can be scary and not regret, fear of punishment, desire for freedom or rebellion against power.
However, it is a already confirmed fact that not only retain, but in justifiable cases also give to third parties all the expressions sought, in these cases there is nothing that protects the personal rights of the internet users.
The most debated example of recent times was the coordinated action against Brazilian pedophiles, when Google delivered to the Brazilian government the information on its website, Orkut, to identify pedophiles.
Instead, people who are worried about the rights of people, in May relieved when the company together with the EFF, an electronic rights organization, successfully demonstrated before the court that it was right in its dispute with the FBI: according to the judgment, it cannot be forced to Google, through no of the points of the constitution to supply any type of information requested in secret by the FBI.
(At the same time the federal government managed to get the pretext of reinforcing the child protection law approved years ago, about fifty thousand web addresses and about a thousand searched phrases, but without getting the search lists of individual users, nor even the complete lists of web pages and keywords of the last two months.)
This is quite contradictory about Google: it is criticized by those who fear to provide your personal data because they think that your privacy, your private life is damaged by starting to use Google’s services, and they rebel against it as against the multinational companies of conservative image.
Meanwhile, the American geek culture and its enthusiasts followers, internautes and users from other countries, see in them the future generation, the "avanguard corporation", not so to its rival, the Microsoft, cataloged by its Windows as the Conqueror of the World, no matter how both struggle for the same goal.
This may happen because Google, unlike Microsoft, does not ask users for any identification code, nor money for their applications, the code is open and the free software package, constantly updated and seems more youthful, more collaborative than the practice of the official software giant.
But it may also be because the geek see accurately the very problematic relationship between the rights of people and the Internet that was just produced by one of the most mentioned keywords in recent years: the Web 2.0.
The Web 2.0 is about collaboration, to leave intentional footprints behind us and take advantage of the available communication channels, and while the measurements of these vary individually, the essence remains the same: showing ourselves.
A normal young man can have a profile on numerous collective pages, from Facebook to Xanga, and can even join them with other services, such as Twitter or the last.fm that offers a list of his music habits, then these can be included in a tracking system such as the FriendFeed or the Blip.fm, can also have a blog, in which automatically appear the latest photos galleries that are stored on the Flickr or Picasa.
We can know numerous cases of which it is revealed that, for example, the girlfriend, by seeing the next morning flow of photos of common friends, understands who spent the previous night with her fraudulent boyfriend or can dismiss the employee of a company because this writes her sincere opinion on her blog about the company’s direction: one thing is safe, the definition of private life has been revalued completely.
A person's "on line" life is what she shows of herself - this is the definition that is hiding behind the behavior of the youth of our days.
And whoever wants to hide something, or at least wants to escape Google’s monopoly, can do it (starting for example with the Scroogle that uses Google’s search system, but doesn’t leave footprints).
There are many people who don’t want to register on the collective pages to prevent them from being found, but Google’s “on line” apps can be replaced, from text writing software to image and news reading apps with alternative versions which do not connect to giant servers nor prepare the most perfect profile possible about us.
The public opinion almost openly awaits the day that Google will show its true face.
The company with its current value of $156 billion is worth more than IBM (140 billion dollars), Intel (124 billion dollars) or Coca-Cola (110 billion dollars), AdWords/AdSense advertising surfaces threaten advertising agencies’ revenue, as the services that are increasingly rapidly introduced cause serious headaches not only for Microsoft, but also numerous other software developers.
Critical observers, however, will find the alarming contradictions too: for example, the top management routinely rejected the employees' protest after doubling the price of the company's childcare, considered too expensive the unlimited number of employees' feed, but all this is nothing compared to the fact that in 2006 Google gave up to the pressure of the Chinese government and the company according to the agreement filtered all information that violated the good morality and interests of the Chinese regime.
One of the company’s internal regulations says they will not announce any new service in advance, but only when it’s already ready to work, which if it’s sure is that the predictable problems of the coming months and years will be able to revolve the World: while some believe that Google’s scan and book and magazine file project will acquire such dimensions that the company will soon be quoted by the U.S. Supreme Court, others fear its Health system, because in it we can create our own complete health profile, with previous analysis, with our doctors and our problems.
And the fact that Google will create a genetic database, will be able to provide a good raw material for science fiction writers, the Scroogled, the popular novel of Cory Doctorow, describes in orwelian form that future, in which a man only of Google’s data can be described alarmantly well.
