The smart car imitates the flight of the bear
What would be the best method to develop technologies in order to avoid collisions, if not the imitation of the sensors of obstacles existing in nature?
For example, the bees.
In a surprising project presented at the CEATEC in Japan, beekeepers gave the starting point for Nissan engineers to design the next generation of collision prevention systems.
Nissan, in cooperation with the University of Tokyo, designed the nature-imitating BR23C car robotic direction system, which was given the characteristics of the bees, with the final goal of creating a system that can avoid all collisions.
During the flight each beef creates its own private oval space that actually looks very much like our safety protective capsule – explained in the exhibition Kazuhhiro Doi, technological director of RP and development and research.
The composite eyes of the bears are able to see in all directions in an angle of more than 300 degrees.
To copy the function of the compound eyes, engineers used the length measurement system by laser rays.
This identifies the obstacles in front of the BR23C within a distance of 2 meters, in an angle of 180 degrees, calculates its distance and sends a signal to the vehicle’s microprocessor that immediately turns into a maneuver to avoid collision.
In a fraction of seconds the obstacle is identified, then the vehicle's robot imitating the movements of the bears, modifies the direction by turning in the necessary measure the wheels.
Unlike any system currently existing, this maneuver is completely instinctive.
“If not so, the vehicle’s robot could not react quickly enough to escape the obstacles,” explains Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the vehicle robot project.
It should react immediately and instinctively, as this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable interior layer of the safety protective capsule, in a layer within which all kinds of collisions are currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what a beef does to avoid other beefs.
This process should be done with an opening and closing of the eyes.
However, unlike the bears, the movement cannot be directed up, down or diagonal, but can only be two-dimensional and exclusively in the rotation direction of the wheels.
In this way, instead of the infinite possibilities that exist for beekeepers to escape other beekeepers, here they only used as a possibility for the auto robot the rotatory movement and acceleration in addition the braking.
The BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and their energy density is higher, meaning they have a longer life than the lithium-ion battery.
According to Andoh, the important thing is the instinctive and intelligent reaction and not the ability to process data, not much less that of storage.
This device in every second should only process some input signals and react according to the case.
It is not necessary to store these data or react with an instinctive logic based on the data of the previous maneuver, so it uses just a few dozen kilobytes of memory.
There is no need for gigabytes or megabytes.
This is the first step in developing the technology to immediately escape the obstacles, which according to Nissan’s calculations, within ten years will be able to be incorporated into the series-made models.
Another possibility for its application is to incorporate the unit into the GPS satellite navigation system to take the driver to his destination, avoiding the obstacles on his way.
