The written version of the $700 billion financial rescue package law has been prepared that will be applied in several stages with the purpose of buying bad credit from banks.
In the first stage, half of the money will be spent.
According to Eastern coast time during the new consultations that lasted until after midnight on Saturday, Congress leaders reached an agreement around the $700 billion financial rescue package in total, after several days of discussion, Reuters.
"We've made significant progress," said Nancy Pelosi, Democratic President of the North American Congress, saying it's only necessary to formalize the agreement in a document.
The commitment on the package was supported by both presidential candidates, Barack Obama and John McCain.
Henry Paulson, the Minister of Finance, speaking about the result of the commitment said: this program will work and will be efficient but other measures are needed.
The written version of the package was published before the opening of the Asian markets, i.e. on Sunday before 8 p.m., according to Washington time (or before 2 p.m. on Monday, according to Central Europe time), without causing a spectacular jump on the stock markets.
On the draft law called the Emergency Law for the Economic Stabilization of the Year 2008, on Monday first will vote the North American Congress and then the Senate.
President George W. Bush on Saturday night consulted with Pelosi and then the White House also celebrated the news about the deal.
We are pleased with the progress achieved during the night and we highly appreciate the efforts of both parties to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy,” White House spokesman Tony Fratto said.
The program is different from the Bush administration’s original proposal to spend all $700 billion to buy poor quality credit fund securities.
Now only half of the $700 billion can be spent, using $250 billion immediately after Congress votes, probably on Monday, of this sum the Ministry of Finance will buy credit fund securities, of poor rating and the fate of another $100 billion depends on the president’s decision.
This program will be controlled by a special body, in which the President of the Federal Reserve will also participate.
The other half of the $700 billion will be spent after a new Congress decision.
According to the law, the Ministry of Finance can apply a combined tactic: it will be able to simultaneously buy bad credits, mortgages and credit fund securities, in addition to other “poison” credits as well.
The purchase may be made in auctions or in direct form - informed the ministry's competent persons.
The law allows affected companies to participate in an insurance program where the financial portfolio guarantees the worrying elements, for which companies will pay the amount corresponding to the predictable damages.
Henry Paulson said: The law thus ensures the necessary financial means, which can even reach even $700 billion to meet the urgent needs of the U.S. financial system, to be the purchase of bad financial means, their insurance or the prevention of risks that could cause the collapse of some major financial institutions.
We do everything we need to be ready to introduce the law as soon as they sign it – he added.
Instead, the chiefs of the banks who are in trouble and are waiting for state aid will be able to count on the official limitation of their compensations, which the U.S. argot calls simply gold falls.
Only in some specific cases payments will be limited, in addition the limitations depend on the form of aid from the Ministry of Finance.
The limitation means that if the ministry purchases in the framework of an auction, an extra tax will be imposed for the gold falls, unless the bank's failed boss is praised.
By directly buying the bad credits the government will act aggressively to ensure that the boss compensations are not exaggerated.
In addition to the above, the existing gold parachute contracts will not be changed, the limitations refer to only the new contracts to stimulate the participation in the program.
This is the first case in the U.S. history that a legal limitation for the revenue of the general directors will be in force, said Democrat Barney Frank, chairman of the Congress committee, responsible for financial services.
The State will also have the right to acquire shares from the banks participating in the program, so the risk of the taxpayers will be reduced, since they will eventually even be able to obtain profits with the transaction as soon as the economy is recovered and with it the bank.
According to the draft law in the next five years the president must submit to Congress a proposition on how to return taxpayers the losses of the financial sector.
Of course, on both sides there were those who expressed their reservations regarding the project.
This is not what the US citizens ordered us, that is, the dollars are not being protected from taxpayers, California Republican Congressman Darrell Issa said.
His Ohio Democratic colleague, Mary Kaptur, said that the measures urged him the same that are responsible for the collapse of Wall Street.
Industrial prices continue to rise
In August 2008, domestic industrial sales prices increased by 0.1 percent compared to last month prices and by 12.9 percent compared to August 2007 prices, the Central Bureau of Statistics (KSH).
Industrial export prices rose 1.1 percent compared to July 2008 and decreased 3.9 percent compared to the previous year.
As a result of the changes in domestic and export prices, industrial production prices increased by 0.7% compared to the previous month and by 3.2% compared to the previous year.
Industrial sales prices increased only at a minimum rate, by 0.1 percent.
Internal sales prices in the processing industry sectors increased minimally, with a 0.1% compared to July.
The greatest increase in the price magnitude occurred in August 2008 in the leather and shoe production sector (2,8 per cent), primarily due to a monthly 4.6 per cent increase in bags and belt and a 2.5 per cent increase in shoes.
The highest price level of plastic and chemical base materials resulted in a significant monthly increase in chemical production branch prices (1.6 percent).
A price decrease occurred in the petrochemical sector, (1,4 per cent), in the production of electrical machines and instruments (0,9 per cent), as well as - in a minimum - in the wood processing sectors (0,1 per cent).
The prices of paper manufacturing, publishing and printing did not change.
In the rest of the processing industry sectors, prices increased between 0.2 and 0.9 percent.
In the supply of electricity, gas, heat and water that represent an important weight within domestic trade, an increase of 0.3 per cent was recorded in August, first due to the effect of the rise of official prices from 1 July.
In a comparison of a twelve-month period – in the domestic sales of the processing sectors – the highest price rise was recorded in the petrochemical sector (32.4 percent).
In the metal manufacturing sector there was an increase of 13.2 percent, while in the food, beverage and tobacco industry, of determining weight, there was an increase of 11 percent.
A decrease in prices was in the textile industry (2,5 percent), as well as in the manufacturing of electrical machines and instruments (0.3 percent).
In the rest of the processing sectors the pace of price growth was between 0.6 and 9.1 percent.
Over the course of the year in the processing industry globally increased prices by 10.2 percent.
The prices of electricity, gas, heat and water supply exceeded the prices of the previous year by 18.7 percent.
In the month of August, among the different sectors of domestic trade the highest monthly price increase (0.7%) was recorded in the sectors of investment goods.
In the consumer goods sectors, prices increased by 0.3 percent, while in the energy and intermediate sectors there were no changes compared to the previous month.
In August 2008, compared to the same month of the previous year, the highest price rise occurred in the energy sector and the intermediate industry (16.8 percent).
In consumer goods manufacturing branches a 6.8% decline and in investment goods a 1.4%.
Industry export prices calculated in HUF increased 1.1 percent compared to the previous month, and compared to 12 months, there was a drop of 3.9 percent.
The cotisation of our national currency in a month decreased by 1.7 per cent compared to the euro and by 7.1 per cent compared to the dollar, compared to August 2007 strengthening by 7.5 per cent compared to the euro and 15.9 per cent compared to the dollar.
