Járóka: The vicious circle of poverty and segregation must be broken
Today the European Summit for Equality of Opportunities has begun in Paris, its host is France which this year is also the turn president of the European Union.
Lívia Járóka, Deputy of the European People's Party for the Fidesz, in her message addressed to the plenary, as one of the main speakers of this professional meeting, attracted attention about segregation in education, because it is one of the most serious violations that hit the Gitan children and is also the biggest obstacle to the prevailing foundation of their interests.
This high-level conference was inaugurated - on behalf of the French presidency - by Xavier Bertrand, French Minister of Employment and Social Affairs and by Vladimir Spidla, European Commissioner responsible for Employment, Social Affairs and Equal Opportunities.
The meeting was attended by representatives of governments, European social interlocutors and representatives of the most important European organizations for the protection of social rights.
Járóka - according to the press office of the Fidesz group in the European Parliament - warned that in addition to discrimination in employment, the Gitanians remain out of the labour market in the first place because of their low level of schooling.
“The majority of young Guitanians have not completed secondary education and due to the poor quality of basic teaching, only one insignificant part can obtain university degree.”
Járóka also highlighted that education, as a fundamental human right, has a decisive role in the prevailing foundation of the other human rights as well.
Investing in the teaching of Chinese children at an early age can strengthen the economy of the EU Member States.
According to the eurodiputate, it is necessary to broadly awareness these issues both among the Gitan and among the non-Gitan.
For the earlier a Gita student starts school, the more chances will have to become an active member of the labour market; through income and consumption taxes they will also contribute to the national budget.
“Gythans, as citizens of the European Union, must be guaranteed the right to a quality education and guaranteed the abolition of the segregated and low-level education,” Lívia Járóka said.
According to the deputy, the objective and active unity of the European Union is necessary to immediately accelerate the processes of school degradation, for that it is of fundamental importance the correct compliance with the existing and planned anti-discriminatory directives.
“We have to break the vicious circle of poverty, segregation and unemployment, we have to offer the possibility that guarantees the democratic space so that they can contribute to the future of Europe as citizens of full rights,” Járóka said.
The objective of the European Summit for Equality of Opportunities, organized annually since the last year’s Berlin Meeting held in the sign of the “European Year of Equality of Opportunities”, is to provide a unique forum to promote the abolition of discrimination and equal opportunities at the European and national level of the Member States.
