MP3 readers under accusation, put the hearing at risk
Listening to high-volume music for a long period of time using portable music devices such as Mp3 readers can cause permanent hearing injuries.
It is what the European Commission refers, that in a statement disseminated in Bruxel quotes the opinion of the Scientific Commission on Emerging and Recently Identified Health Risk (Csrseri) of the EU, published today.
“From this scientific opinion – it is read in the note – arises that 5-10% of those who, for a period of at least 5 years, listen to music with portable music apparatus weekly for more than one hour a day having the high-volume apparatus risk a permanent loss of hearing capacity.”
“I am worried that such a high number of young people who frequently use portable music devices and high-acoustic cell phones can unconsciously ruin their ears in an irreparable way,” says Meglena Kuneva.
“From scientific evidence – the EU’s responsibility follows – a clear risk emerges and we must react quickly.
What matters is to raise awareness of consumers and render this information of public domain.
We need to review, in addition, the existing control systems in the light of this scientific opinion, so that they are widely effective and have the passage with the new technology.”
Bruxel had asked the Independent Scientific Committee to examine the problem, seeing the great use of portable music apparatus and the increase in the number of young people exposed to the noise that that originates.
"The scientists - concludes the EU executive - confirm that it is a cause of concern and the European Commission will now examine together with the Member States and stakeholders what measures could eventually be taken to better protect children and adolescents from the noise exposure from portable music devices and related devices."
Currently, there is already a European security standard that limits to 100 dB the noise level of the portable music devices, but concern increases as the hearing damage that can be derived from an excessive exposure to such noise sources.
It is possible to greatly limit these damages by resorting to solutions such as reducing levels and time exposure to noise.
According to its opinion, the EU Scientific Committee notes that if users of portable music devices listen to high volume (more than 89 decibels) music for just 5 hours a week, they exceed the current limit for the maximum noise consented at the workplace.
Those who listen to music in such conditions for longer periods risk a permanent loss of hearing capacity after a period of 5 years.
This means that it affects 5-10% of the users of such devices and the number can be quantified between 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
