Students victims of expensive rental, up to 900 euros for a room
The rental market for university students does not know the crisis.
According to the latest Sunia survey, the rental syndicate, renting an individual room could cost a student 900 euros in Milan, 700 in Florence, 650 in Naples, 600 in Rome.
“The phenomenon has already assumed very serious characteristics to the point of excluding the right to study a large part of young people for the highly cost that the family would have to sustain – explains the head of the Sunia studies office, Laura Mariani – in these cities the strong demand has completely deformed the market to a point of triggering a process of widespread increase even for residents.”
Except that in most cases the rental offers contain a series of violations: free type contracts, unregistered, no limit of canon, under rental liable.
For Sunia, extraordinary interventions are required that, through the review of the taxation, the prices can be regulated.
Looking in detail the survey, we see that in Milan, for a bed in Brianza area, serve approximately 450 euros; for a individual room from a minimum of 650 (Bande Nere area) to an average value of 800 (Lambiate area, Udine and Fiera) to a maximum of 900 (in Victoria area).
In Florence a bed costs an average of 350/400 euros, a room approximately 700.
In Bologna, where students concentrate in the areas near the University, they serve 250/280 euros for a bed in a double room and from 370 to 500 for an individual.
In Rome in the central areas near the University(San Lorenzo, Plaza Bolonia) you ask about 600 euros for a single room and 450 for a bed in a double room.
Only slightly lower values (550 euros for a single room) in areas near other Universities(Ostiense and Cinecittà).
Economy is made only if the peripheral area is changed: 300 euros for a bed and 450 euros for an individual room in the Prenestina, Centocelle area and surroundings.
In Naples for a bed you serve 300/450 euros, for a room you spend from 400 to 600 euros, with the highest prices in the Policlinic, Vomero and Colli Aminei areas.
In Bari for one bed you serve 250/350 euros, at least 350 for one individual.
In the youngest cities the prices are lower in absolute deadlines, but it has a greater weight in the city’s economy.
In cities such as Perugia, where the rental phenomenon to students and non-community is more frequent, a subsequent anomaly is recorded: an increase of 25/30% of the canon to foreign students compared to the Italians.
Goodbye to the old Paradiso cinema, cities cancel historic rooms
Historic cinema rooms close favouring the Multiplex.
“A city without cinema in a blind city is like a face without eyes.”
The image offered by director Giuseppe Tornatore photographer with effectively what is happening in the big Italian urban centers and also in the cities of the province.
The process of marginalization of the cinemas, which with the birth of the great meticons in the periphery and the consequent disappearance of the monkey rooms in the central areas of the city, is an inevitable and indisputable event with all the characteristics of a true cultural crime.
To disappear almost always are historical places, full of memory,"it's like a friend died, a acquaintance with whom a piece of place and so much emotion was shared," Observe the director of the new cinema Paradiso, the film that twenty years ago won the cousin Oscar and the great prize of the jury in Cannes, which told the poetry of a province cinema and the nostalgia for the way of living the cinema that lost forever.
The figures given by the Annec, the main association of merchants, speak clear: in the last five years have closed 316 traditional cinemas, and to pay the majority are above all the rooms of the main cities: 10 less in Florence, 9 less in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most suffered by the closures are as the first, Emilia-Romaña with 82 movies less, followed by Toscana (44) and Lombardy (41).
It is a demonstration that the responsible for their disappearance is the advent of the multiplex, they are own of these three Italian regions that have recorded the greatest number of new meticone cinemas: 195 screens more in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 be in Toscana than in Emilia-Romania.
“The Italian exercise has evolved irrationally,” observes Paolo Protti, the chairman of the Annex, “it would be useful that new structures are built but the remaining of those already existing should be guaranteed, because when a city room is closed, not all of its frequenters are willing to transfer to the meticons.
Not to mention the lack of funds in favour of traders: the previous debt of the state is approximately 10 million euros.
It is shameful from the ethical and moral point of view that the government does not respect the laws that exist.
To maintain the sector would serve between 16 and 18 million euros a year.”
Interesting the case of Bologna, the first Italian city concerned with the closures, decided to repair with the signature of a protocol between the municipality and Anec, the first of this type in Italy to promote and tutel the cinema mono sala be in the historic center than in the periphery.
Among the foreseeable standards there are tax facilitation intermediates in favour of the managers and advantages for the public in terms of mobility: viewers will be able to enter the area of limited traffic and will have special rates for parking.
“It’s an initiative that I like,” observes Giuseppe Tornatore, “and I hope other cities will follow the example of Bologna by putting on other measures.
It is true that in order to contrast the extra power of the meticons, the traditional rooms have to improve the quality of sound and image because the audience today is more demanding.
